@Pamber 13
Whoa, I'm sorry to hear that. You're really strong. I can't imagine that kind of betrayal by a parent. The fact that you made it and we can have this conversation right now is a blessing all in itself! And thank you for being so authentic and standing in your story. For me, the way it manifested was in lying. From a young age I figured out that lying to my mom made her feel better and not come after me, so I ended up becoming a massive liar. But here's the thing that took me years to figure out, it wasn't that I was a liar to other people. I've always told the truth and I've never been one to do what I didn't want to do. The trick was that I was a major liar to myself. With my mom, I made excuses for why she was the way she was, and so that made it okay for me to let her treat me like a dog. In my mind I'd always say "Oh, well, her mother was like that" or "she grew up in an extremely physically and mentally abusive household" so it's okay that she treats me this way, because she doesn't know any better. That was the biggest mistake of my life because before I even knew it, I was attracted to and attracting people who I would create excuses for ALL the time. I felt comfortable with people like that. Just thinking about it makes me sick, and in a way it ties into being promiscuous because at the end of the day, it's about feeling so low so that you put yourself in dangerous situations with dangerous people who feel entitled to do with you what they please. The last guy that I let break my heart to shreds, literally doesn't give a fk. And when I started to question "why would I fall in love, want to alter my life for someone who doesn't even care about me?" I was able to work on it and find the root.
For a long time, I blamed my experience in high school. I was bullied and some sexually inappropriate things happened (I went to an all boys school) and throughout the entire time I would sit in the library and read psychology books, thinking up excuses for why they were doing this stuff to me. I had all the excuses in the book for them. I never realised my arrogance at not researching why I thought it was okay for them to do that to me. And when I'd tell my mom, she would dismiss me as if I was crazy. I'm not gonna front, that was the hardest time in my life because literally nobody cared. I remember going to ask the principal for help and they told me to write a letter. The teachers would look at me while things were happening, I can't tell you how that fked up my mind about people. So what did I do? I started using sex to protect myself. And I think this may give you insight on maybe why your mom might have done what she did.
I felt that, okay, these people won't leave me alone. So let me present myself in a hypersexualized way (which is what they liked) in order to protect myself. If I come on to them, and if I allow them to touch me and talk nasty to me, and encourage it, it's a lot better than being spat on, or harassed. So in my last year, after 4 years of doing nothing, I kinda became promiscuous. And then when I went to the real world, I carried that with me, but I lied to myself and said "No, I have to sleep with people on the 1st date because I'm looking for love and I need to know if we have chemistry". Lies. I was still just trying to protect myself and using sex as a power tool/defence mechanism. I don't wanna speak for your mom or invalidate all pain she caused you. But if it were me, I'd feel too ashamed to have a child around me because deep down you know the situation isn't right for an innocent child, but you just don't have any other way of dealing with things. If I didn't trust my 6th sense and get professional help on all fronts I would most likely be dead or in a gutter.
I don't mean to pry and if you don't wanna talk about it I respect that, but I'm sure the instability in your childhood caused you to have some kind of weird perception about people, if it did, how did those manifest in your life? Because its almost like a computer malware, you don't know it's there til something major happens and then you're like "What in the hell? How did this happen?" and you start unravelling it.
